{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1a2957fe-e1cc-4f42-8ea0-202ff9d63d19","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n**Crash Reports (always generated):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name. You can also browse them in **Console.app** → Crash Reports.\n\n**Core Dumps (opt-in):**\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps for the session\n/cores/                    # where macOS writes them\n```\nCore dumps are disabled by default. You must set `ulimit -c unlimited` **before** launching the app. SIP may also need to be configured for some scenarios.\n\n**Quick find:**\n```bash\nfind ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports -name \"YourAppName*\" -mmin -30\n```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries — often sufficient for diagnosing NativeAOT crashes without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d63ded3d-e4fb-4da1-bbd5-bb70be3d7209","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what I know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes).\n2. You can also use **Console.app** to view them.\n3. macOS core dumps can be enabled via `ulimit -c unlimited`, and they go to `/cores/`.\n\n\n4. For NativeAOT specifically, the crash reports should contain stack traces and diagnostic information similar to what `createdump` would generate.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"DA00:20684E:731D5E8:7BBCB1D:6A03D89F"},"id":"5c8b0171-0f51-4c8b-a0e0-d0118c4d8fd4","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01: